        <section class="mb-16">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center mb-8 text-cyan-500">Traumatic Conditions & Pathophysiology</h2>
            
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 md:grid-cols-2 gap-8 mb-12">
                <div class="bg-gray-800 p-6 rounded-lg shadow-xl">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-center text-cyan-400">Blunt Trauma Danger</h3>
                     <p class="text-center mb-4 text-gray-300">From falls or MVCs. The biggest threat is widespread damage to the GI organs.</p>
                    <div class="chart-container">
                        <canvas id="bluntTraumaChart"></canvas>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-gray-800 p-6 rounded-lg shadow-xl">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-center text-cyan-400">Penetrating Trauma Danger</h3>
                    <p class="text-center mb-4 text-gray-300">From GSWs, stabbings, or other penetrating damage.</p>
                    <div class="chart-container">
                        <canvas id="penetratingTraumaChart"></canvas>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
            
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center mb-8">Treatment Protocols</h2>
            <div class="grid grid-cols-1 lg:grid-cols-2 gap-8">
                <div class="bg-gray-800 p-6 rounded-lg shadow-xl">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-center text-green-500">Volvulus Treatment (Medical)</h3>
                    <p class="text-center text-gray-400 -mt-2 mb-4 italic"> A condition where a loop of intestine twists on itself, cutting off its own blood supply.</p>
                     <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-700 rounded-lg flowchart-step">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg text-green-400">BLS Care</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-300">Position of comfort, high-flow O2, treat for shock, rapid transport.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-700 rounded-lg flowchart-step">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg text-green-400">ALS Care</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-300">Establish IV access combat shock from tissue death. Provide pain management.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-700 rounded-lg flowchart-step">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg text-green-400">Hospital Care</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-300">Emergency surgery is required to untwist the intestine (de-rotation) and remove any dead tissue.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
                <div class="bg-gray-800 p-6 rounded-lg shadow-xl">
                    <h3 class="text-2xl font-bold mb-2 text-center text-red-500">Evisceration Treatment (Trauma)</h3>
                    <p class="text-center text-gray-400 -mt-2 mb-4 italic">Intestines / Organs that are protruding from an open abdomenial wound.</p>
                    <div class="space-y-4">
                        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-700 rounded-lg flowchart-step">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg text-red-400">BLS Care</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-300">Do <b>NOT</b> push organs in. Cover with a moist, sterile dressing, then an occlusive dressing. Treat for shock.</p>
                        </div>
                        <div class="p-4 bg-gray-700 rounded-lg flowchart-step">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg text-red-400">ALS Care</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-300">Supportive care, establish IV access, pain management may be considered, rapid transport.</p>
                        </div>
                         <div class="p-4 bg-gray-700 rounded-lg flowchart-step">
                            <h4 class="font-bold text-lg text-red-400">Hospital Care</h4>
                            <p class="text-gray-300">Immediate surgery to inspect for internal damage and repair the abdominal wall.</p>
                        </div>
                    </div>
                </div>
            </div>
        </section>
        
        <section class="mb-12 max-w-3xl mx-auto">
            <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-center mb-8 text-yellow-500">BLS GI/GU Tips</h2>
            <ul class="space-y-4 text-lg">
                <li class="bg-gray-800 p-4 rounded-lg flex items-center shadow-xl"><span class="text-3xl mr-4">❤️</span><div><strong class="text-yellow-400">Notice The Signs:</strong> Tachycardia is an early sign of shock. A normal BP can drop suddenly.</div></li>
                <li class="bg-gray-800 p-4 rounded-lg flex items-center shadow-xl"><span class="text-3xl mr-4">👃</span><div><strong class="text-yellow-400">Smell is a Clue:</strong> The distinct smell of melena or a GI bleed is a powerful, unforgettable clue.</div></li>
                <li class="bg-gray-800 p-4 rounded-lg flex items-center shadow-xl"><span class="text-3xl mr-4">🥋</span><div><strong class="text-yellow-400">Look for Seatbelt Marks:</strong> A bruise across the abdomen is a major red flag for underlying organ damage after an MVC.</div></li>
                <li class="bg-gray-800 p-4 rounded-lg flex items-center shadow-xl"><span class="text-3xl mr-4">🤫</span><div><strong class="text-yellow-400">Dont Soely Go Off Pain:</strong> A stomach full of blood might only cause mild pain. Look at the whole picture, not just the pain level.</div></li>
                <li class="bg-gray-800 p-4 rounded-lg flex items-center shadow-xl"><span class="text-3xl mr-4">💧</span><div><strong class="text-yellow-400">Always Treat for Shock:</strong> High-flow O2, a blanket, and a supine position are simple interventions that save lives.</div></li>
            </ul>
        </section>

        <footer class="text-center border-t border-gray-700 pt-8 mt-12">
